sentence: US stocks closed fractionally lower as economic data and testimony from Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell failed to provide a great deal of direction for investors Tuesday.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average, S&P 500 and Nasdaq Composite Index ended up dipping into negative territory late after a choppy session.
The Dow was dragged down in part by losses in shares of Caterpillar ( CAT ), which was downgraded by UBS, and Home Depot ( HD ), which posted results that fell short of Wall Street expectations.

Powell, in his semi-annual testimony to Congress, said in prepared remarks that the economic outlook is positive, although "over the past few months we have seen some crosscurrents and conflicting signals."
Powell testified in the Senate Tuesday and on Wednesday he is scheduled to appear before the House financial services committee.
The economic news released Tuesday didn't provide a huge spark for the market.
The February Conference Board consumer confidence index rose to 131.4 from a revised 121.7 and ahead of the 125 consensus estimate.
Meanwhile, housing starts fell 11% in December, more than expected, to the lowest since September 2016.
The data had been delayed by the partial government shutdown.
Housing permits, however, rose 0.4% to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of 1.326 million.
The Richmond Fed manufacturing index jumped to 16 in February from a negative 2 in January.

FTSE 100 was down 0.45% to 7,151.12

Hang Seng Index was down 0.65% to 28,772.06

Shanghai China Composite Index was down 0.67% to 2,941.52

(+) FTNW (+112.84%) Won $116 mln of contracts during Jan and Feb

(-) NLS (-23.75%) Downgraded at Craig Hallum to hold from buy
